  "text": "The 10 nonredundant P. mirabilis isolates were genotyped by ribotyping and pulsed-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE) (Fig.  1) . Genomic DNAs were prepared from the 10 Proteus mirabilis isolates and 3 unrelated isolates. Ribotyping was performed as previously described (4) with endonuclease EcoRI (Boehringer). PFGE of restricted genomic DNA was performed with a CHEF-DR III apparatus (Bio-Rad Laboratories) as previously reported [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , after DNA digestion by endonuclease NotI (New England Biolabs, Hertfordshire, United Kingdom). Lambda ladder (PFGE Marker 1; Boehringer Mannheim, Meylan, France) was used as a DNA molecular size marker. With both methods, the 10 OXA-23-producing isolates had indistinguishable (9 out of 10 strains) or closely related (1 strain displaying one genetic event of difference by PFGE only) patterns, which differed from those of non-OXA-23-producing P. mirabilis strains by more than seven DNA fragments in PFGE. The 10 OXA-23-producing P. mirabilis isolates therefore derived from a single clonal strain, designated CFO239, which had become established in our hospital over a period of at least 4 years.",
